4047. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 612273904
T1  - Clinical and immunologic profile of women with recurrent pregnancy losses in a tertiary hospital in the Philippines
T3  - 15th International Congress on Antiphospholipid Antibodies. Istanbul Turkey.
A1  - Mondragon A.V.
A1  - De Jesus M.S.A.
A1  - Aleta L.T.A. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Background: Recurrent pregnancy loss (RPL) affects 1-5% of women with most cases due to autoimmune causes and around 40-50% are idiopathic. Commonly associated with RPL is the antiphospholipid syndrome (APS). Recent studies have explored a distinction between vascular and obstetric APS. Investigations have revealed that a number of patients present only with pregnancy morbidities alongside antiphospholipid antibodies (aPL). In the Philippines, the Philippine Obstetrical and Gynecological Society has released its own practice guidelines on RPL, however local studies on RPL have been lacking. Method(s): We reviewed the clinical features and immunologic profile of 60 patients with a history of at least two pregnancy losses from 2010 to 2015 followed up at a tertiary university hospital. Of these, only 42 had complete records of pregnancy outcomes. Result(s): The age of patients was 32.25+/-0.71 years (range: 20 to 43; median: 34). There was a total of 196 previous pregnancies among the patients, 133 (67.85%) of which were abortions and 37 (18.88%) were preterm deliveries. Co-morbidities present in these patients were: hypertension (11), diabetes mellitus (7), asthma (6), polycystic ovary syndrome (5), and systemic lupus erythematosus (2). Repeat test determination was performed in 13 patients, only two patients fulfilled the Sydney criteria, one in category I, one in IIa. In those with single determination for aPL, 29 were reactive for LA, nine for aCL, and none for abeta2GPI. Multiple test positivity (aCL and LA), seen in only one patient, was associated with preeclampsia and HELLP syndrome. Single positivity of any of the aPLs was not associated with any obstetric complication (miscarriage, preterm delivery, intrauterine growth restriction, preeclampsia, and thrombosis). Conclusion(s): This study shows that there is a low percentage of patients who repeat tests for aPL. Other mechanisms may explain pregnancy morbidities in this study population, which will need additional testing. APS could be one explanation but other immunologic factors could be involved in these cases. Repeat testing will elaborate associations between aPL and obstetric morbidities as seen in other studies. Further studies, particularly prospective studies on RPL may provide us with more information in managing these conditions better.
