4051. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72341665
T1  - Adolescent bariatric surgery: Identifying comorbidities and evaluating success of an interdisciplinary treatment team
T3  - 2016 Annual Meeting of the Society for Adolescent Health and Medicine, SAHM 2016. Washington, DC United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Weiss A.L.
A1  - Taguchi M.
A1  - Aslam S.
A1  - Murr M.M. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Purpose: Adolescent obesity and severe obesity have increased significantly over the past thirty years. Most obese adolescents become obese adults and develop medical diseases and psychosocial problems. Adolescent obesity treatment often focuses on lifestyle modifications, and can be effective in the short-term but has disappointing long-term results. Bariatric surgery induces durable and sustainable weight loss in adults, remission of comorbidities, and increased longevity. Adolescent bariatric surgery increased five-fold from 1997-2003 and is emerging as an effective treatment for adolescents with severe obesity. We present an exploratory study to evaluate the prevalence of medical and psychological co-morbidities and success of an interdisciplinary team approach in treating adolescent severe obesity. Method(s): We initiated a weekly interdisciplinary adolescent bariatric clinic in collaboration with our established adult bariatric center. Adolescents >=16 years, with a BMI >=35 with co-morbidities, or BMI>=40, are assessed by an adolescent medicine physician as well as an experienced bariatric psychologist, dietician, and exercise physiologist. Patients are seen monthly for at least 6 months prior to being considered for surgery. Visits focus on medical weight loss, work-up and treatment of co-morbidities, extensive nutrition education, comprehensive psychological evaluation, and screening for surgical candidates based on comprehension, adherence, and family support. IRB approval was obtained for data collection. Descriptive statistics were performed. Result(s): Seven adolescent patients have been evaluated; one patient presented once and has not returned, presumably due to loss of insurance. Six females (86%) and one male (14%) completed one to four visits. Mean age at initial visit was 17.3 years (S.D.1.3); mean initial BMI was 48.6 kg.m2 (S.D. 10.8). Patients have attempted up to four different prior weight loss programs. Co-morbidities based on our work-up include: vitamin D deficiency (57%); polycystic ovarian syndrome (57%); pre-hypertension (43%); dyslipidemia (29%); iron deficiency (29%); elevated ALT (14%); pre-diabetes (14%); and obstructive sleep apnea (14%). On initial psychological testing with the Beck Depression Inventory (BDI), two patients (29%) reported symptoms of moderate depression, and one patient reported symptoms of mild depression and severe anxiety (14%). On the Impact of Weight on Quality of Life - Kids (IWQOL-Kids), two patients (29%) had significantly lower quality of life compared to other adolescents undergoing bariatric surgery, and another two patients' (29%) overall quality of life was in the normal range but below average for body esteem. With our approach two patients have shown consistent weight loss (up to 6.8 kg), two have maintained weight within 1 kg, and two have gained weight (up to 8.1 kg). Conclusion(s): We identified a high prevalence of medical and psychological co-morbidities, treatment of which must be an integral part of any medical or surgical weight loss program. As bariatric surgery becomes more common in adolescents, more data is needed to assess the true prevalence of co-morbidities and to identify which adolescents may be better suited for surgery based on demographics, co-morbidities, family support, and psychological issues, as assessed by an interdisciplinary treatment team.
