A1  - Khandalavala B. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Background More than one-third of adults and 17% of youth in the United States are obese. The average caloric intake for Americans has increased by 150 to 300 calories per day over the last 30 years with roughly 50% of these calories come from liquids, mainly sugar-sweetened beverages (SSB). Obesity is associated with increased risk of a number of adverse cardiovascular diseases that includes diabetes, heart disease, fatty liver, sleep apnea, PCOS and other health conditions. SSBs have been independently associated with many of these conditions. Research has shown that the chances of developing type 2 diabetes for those who consume SSBs regularly increases by 26%. Hence we proposed a feasibility study in a high risk population to assess the current consumption of beverages in a Family Medicine Clinic at an academic medical center in Omaha Nebraska. The BEVQ-15 is a valid and reliable survey that estimates mean daily intake of a variety of beverages consumed. Methods Assessment of SSB in the clinic can be accessed via various food frequency surveys. The BEVQ 15 was elected to be used as a tool due to brevity and being compatible with lower literacy levels up to the 4th grade level. Feasibility was determined to include acceptability, demand, implementation, practicality and adaptation. Results We collected 311 completed surveys over a three month period. Two research assistants approached patients in the patient room, proposed enrollment, to ensure privacy, and prior to arrival of the provider. Time required less than 5 minutes on average. There was no disruption in the flow of the clinic. Patients were highly receptive to the interaction. Conclusion Using the BEVQ - 15 to assess consumption of SSB in a teaching primary care clinic involving Family Practice residents was feasible. Further essential research and targeted intervention can be conducted in this high risk population.
