4064. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72296592
T1  - Clinically important pharmaceuticals and dietary supplements cause loss of OCT4 and REX1 potency factors and slows growth in mouse embryos through AMPK signaling
T3  - 64th Annual Meeting of the Pacific Coast Reproductive Society. Rancho Mirage, CA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Bolnick A.D.
A1  - Kilburn B.
A1  - Abdulhasan M.A.
A1  - Yang Y.
A1  - Shamir A.
A1  - Puscheck E.E.
A1  - Rappolee D.A. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - BACKGROUND: Prescribed AMPK-activated protein kinase (AMPK) agonists such as metformin are used to treat metabolic syndromes and anovulatory patients with polycystic ovary syndrome. AMPK is likely involved with potency loss that affects differentiation and repetitive exposure of multiple dietary supplements (DS) and pharmaceutical AMPK agonists have possible toxicity through potency/stemness loss and forced differentiation of stem cells of the early embryo. As a model for stress in vivo, we hypothesize that clinically relevant AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) agonists may cause unwanted early pregnancy complications. Agonists include pharma (metformin and aspirin), and DS (bromo-3,3' diindolylmethane). OBJECTIVE(S): To test AMPK agonists and antagonists in mouse embryos as a model for stress in vivo by assaying for AMPK mediated rapid potency loss, or AMPK function via pharma and DS in slowing cultured embryo progression. MATERIALS AND METHODS: Fresh and frozen mouse embryos were used for comparative analysis. Zygotes were cultured to the 2-cell stage, and then treated with AMPK agonist A769662 to induce stress, +/- the AMPK antagonist compound C, or without stress in the presence of AMPK agonists, metformin and aspirin, or DSs. We analyzed potency loss by immuno-fluorescence using antibodies to Rex1 and Oct4 potency factors and determined growth rates and progression of embryos to blastocyst stage. RESULT(S): AMPK agonists, A769662, metformin and ASA significantly reduced nuclear OCT4 and REX1 expression in 2-cell embryos. The potency loss was rescued by the AMPK antagonist compound C. Metformin and aspirin slowed embryo growth in the 2nd day, and caused death by the 4th day. These effects were completely reversed by compound C. Dietary supplements also slowed embryo growth in the 2nd day and were reversed by AMPK antagonist. Frozen embryos did not alter the final outcomes. CONCLUSION(S): Clinically important pharma and DSs activate AMPK and a growing list of stem cell potency factors undergoes AMPK-dependent loss. Fresh and frozen embryos yielded similar results. AMPKagonists mediated anabolic-to-catabolic shifts as in TSCs and slowing growth. Our data suggests a possible toxicity range of single or multiple AMPK agonists prescribed to improve fertility or used by pregnant women ad hoc. AMPK appears to be the "master regulatory" enzyme that mediates stress-induced loss of potency factors in the totipotent 2 cell embryo that are important later in pluripotent embryonic stem cells and multipotent trophoblast stem cells.
