T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Eissa A.
A1  - Mehta A.
A1  - Tuck S. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Background Mental illness is one of the leading causes of maternal death in the UK. The number of women committing suicide during pregnancy or postnatally has not fallen over the past decade. It is also associated with maternal deaths from other causes. Case A 32-year-old woman, who came to the UK 5 years ago, booked with a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus, polycystic ovarian syndrome and mental illness. She had a complicated social history and was diagnosed with hypothyroidism. At 31 weeks of gestation, her mental condition deteriorated severely and she became very paranoid. She refused to eat, to take medication or to be monitored. She threw her food on the floor and threatened her caregivers and her husband with a knife (from her breakfast cutlery). A multidisciplinary decision was reached to deliver her because of the high risk to her life. However, she was deemed not to have the capacity to give or withhold informed consent and her husband failed to see that delivery was in her best interests and did not agree. Hence, the Obstetrician, aided by the hospital's Legal Advisor, obtained a judicial decision from the Court of Protection to deliver her by an emergency caesarean section. Discussion Physicians involved in maternal, infant care and psychiatric services, frequently come across peripartum mental health problems. This case illustrates how mental illness in pregnancy poses significant challenges to healthcare givers, especially when other medical conditions coexist.
