A1  - Kazemi M.
A1  - McBreairty L.
A1  - Chilibeck P.
A1  - Zello G.A.
A1  - Pierson R.A.
A1  - Chizen D.R. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Background: Women with Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS) often develop impaired glucose control and loss of insulin sensitivity. Obesity, a frequent PCOS co-morbidity, can exacerbate PCOS metabolic abnormalities, by inducing glucose intolerance and insulin resistance (IR). Aim(s): To explore the link between the body mass index (BMI) and blood glucose control in women with PCOS. Method(s): A 2h 75 g glucose tolerance test (OGTT), glycated hemoglobin (HbA1c), and homeostasis model assessment of IR (HOMA) were measured in 200 women with PCOS (18-38y). Result(s): BMI was positively correlated with 2h blood glucose levels (r=0.39, p<0.01), HbA1c levels (r=0.20, p<0.01), and HOMA score (r=0.50, p<0.01). Obese women (BMI >=30 kg/m2) showed abnormally increased HOMA scores (3.4+/-0.3 vs 1.0+/-0.3; p<0.01) and higher levels of 2h blood glucose (6.8+/-0.2 vs. 5.3+/-0.2 mmol/ L; p<0.01) than women with BMI <30 kg/m2). Fifteen of 41 (36.5%) women with class III obesity showed impaired glucose tolerance (IGT), versus 14/46 (30.4%) in class II, and 5/31 (16%) in class I. Only 2/44 (2%) women with healthy BMI exhibited IGT. Conclusion(s): IGT and IR were most prevalent in obesity class II and III; however, OGTT and IR should be evaluated in all women with PCOS regardless of obesity class.
