4072. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72271132
T1  - The role of insulin-like growth factor 1 (IGF1) in polycystic ovarian syndrome in patients with non-alcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD)
T3  - Digestive Disease Week 2016, DDW 2016. San Diego, CA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Orciga M.-A.P.
A1  - Younoszai Z.
A1  - Yao K.
A1  - Keaton M.
A1  - Baranova A.
A1  - Birerdinc A.
A1  - Younossi Z.M. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - Background and Aim: Obesity continues to be a growing epidemic of the 21st century with a variety of metabolic, cardiovascular and reproductive consequences. Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) is found in more than 30% of obese women, and 70% of PCOS patients have insulin resistance. Given the lack of diagnostic biomarker for early detection of this disorder and its frequent co-occurrence with NAFLD, we sought to characterize the levels of IGF1, a hepatocyte secreted growth factor, and its receptor in obese NAFLD patients with PCOS and non-PCOS. Method(s): We included 34 biopsy-proven NAFLD patients with PCOS (n=17) and or without PCOS (n=17). Both groups were matched for age and BMI and had corresponding sera and visceral adipose tissue. Compared groups were selected to include equal number of patients with diabetes mellitus (DM). IGF1R expression and serum levels of IGF1 were quantified along with other metabolic and inflammatory related genes and proteins. Result(s): PCOS patients with DM had significantly lower expression of IGF1R than non-PCOS with DM (p<.04). In PCOS patients, a trend to have lower IGF1R expression was noted (NS) as compared to the non-PCOS group. When non-DM patients with PCOS were compared to that with no PCOS, no significant differences were seen in adipose IGF1R expression or in circulating levels of IGF1. However, ADRA2A, a sympathetic receptor regulating lipolysis, was downregulated in adipose PCOS patients (p<.0002). DM and non- DM PCOS patients (p<.0493 and p<.0026, respectively) followed this trend when compared to non-PCOS patients. In PCOS patients, expression of IGF1R inversely correlated with circulating levels of IL-17 (p<.0484, r=-.48) and leptin expression in adipose (p<.0037, r=- .504). TNFalpha expression was also positively correlated with IGF1R (p<.0001, r=.814) while inversely correlated with ADRA2A (p<.0219, r=-.551). Conclusion(s): IGF1R might play a role in its development of PCOS in NAFLD patients with DM. Lipolysis regulation with ADRA2A is also implicated in pathogenesis of PCOS in obese NAFLD patients independent of their DM state. TNFalpha expression, an inflammatory cytokine, serves as a link between the two pathways. Its expression levels negatively correlates with ADRA2A while positively correlating with IGF1R expression.
