4073. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72226919
T1  - Effects of a combined supplementation of alpha-lipoic acid and myoinositol on endocrine and metabolic features in overweight pcos patients
T3  - 63rd Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2016. Montreal, QC Canada.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - De Cicco S.
A1  - Tropea A.
A1  - Valentina I.
A1  - Daniela R.
A1  - Di Florio C.
A1  - Tagliaferri V.
A1  - Scarinci E.
A1  - Lanzone A.
A1  - Apa R. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Oral supplementation with myo-inositol, a new insulin sensitizer agent was demonstrated to enhance insulin sensitivity and improve the clinical and hormonal characteristics of patients in PCOS. Moreover Alpha-lipoic acid (ALA), a biological antioxidant, has been reported to improve glucose control in patients with type 2 diabetes, presumably by improving insulin sensitivity and reduction of oxidative stress. This study investigates the potential role of these two molecules in improving PCOS characteristics METHODS: Forty overweight PCOS women (BMI>25; age range 18-35 years) were enrolled. Anthropometric characteristics, hirsutism score, ovarian ultrasound, an oral glucose tolerance test and hormonal parameters, including AMH were evaluated before and after combined treatment of alpha-lipoic acid (800 mg), myoinositol (2000 mg) and folic acid (400 mcg) daily for six months. RESULT(S): All patients completed the study therapy. A significant improvement in mean F-G score and BMI was obtained after six months of treatment, while WHR values did not significantly changed. All studied patients experienced a significant increase of number of cycles in six months. A significant ireduction of androgen levels (in terms of free androgen index, androstenedione, DHEAS) was observed. At baseline, AMH serum levels were above the normal range and after six months of treatment we observed a significant decrease. At baseline, participants presented a mean insulinemic response to OGTT and a normal peripheral insulin sensitivity expressed as HOMA-IR. After therapy, we did not observe a significant modification in peripheral insulin sensitivity and in insulin secretion during the OGTT CONCLUSION(S): This combined therapy was shown to restore the menstrual pattern and to improve the hormonal milieu in PCOS women, with a mechanism that, albeit not fully clarified, seems to be insulin independent and instead targeted to the ovary itself. Further investigations on a larger population are needed to confirm these results and to elucidate the specific mechanism of action of this therapy.
