4074. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72226918
T1  - Changes in human skeletal muscle associated with PCOS
T3  - 63rd Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2016. Montreal, QC Canada.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Berger J.J.
A1  - Bates G.W.
A1  - Gower B.A.
A1  - Bamman M.M. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: PCOS has been associated with numerous metabolic abnormalities including the Metabolic Syndrome (MetS) However, the underlying mechanism(s) have not been clearly elucidated. Previously we demonstrated alterations in skeletal muscle fiber type and decreased estrogen (ER), insulin (IR), and androgen (AR) receptor gene expression with PCOS. Since skeletal muscle represents the major site for insulin mediated glucose disposal, we sought to determine alterations in skeletal muscle glucose metabolism that could explain this relationship. METHOD(S): In patients with PCOS (NIH criteria), baseline labs, anthropomorphic measurements and vastus lateralis muscle biopsies were obtained (n=10) and compared to age and race matched controls (n=10). Protein levels of the ER alpha, AR-A, and AR-B were evaluated using routine western blot techniques. Phosphorylation levels of second messengers involved in glucose homeostasis were also examined. RESULT(S): The PCOS group had a significantly elevated BMI (33.7+1.8 vs 25.8+1.2 , p=0.03) higher fasting insulin (7.74 +/- 1.24 vs. 13.86 +/- 19.47 uU/ml, p<0.05), lower SHBG (95.05 +/- 23.22 vs. 41.68 +/- 4.69 nmol/L, p<0.05), higher triglyceride levels (74.7 +/- 11.55 vs 144.2 +/- 22.77 mg/ dL, p<0.05) and lower HDL cholesterol (61.6 +/- 3.82 vs 47 +/- 3.83 mg/dL, p<0.05) compared to controls. Protein levels for ER-alpha (185+/-27 vs. 47.7+/-14.8 A.U., p<0.001) and AR-beta (105.4+/-15.9 vs. 33.9+/-16.2 A.U., p<0.001) were significantly lower in the PCOS subjects compared to controls. There was no difference in AR-alpha protein levels (107.7+/-24.2 vs. 168.4+/-66.4 A.U., NS). Second messenger pathways involved with glucose homeostasis revealed lower phospho-Akt levels in the PCOS group (217.9+/-43.3 vs. 57.1+/-21 A.U., p<0.05). Levels of phospho-MAPK, phospho-IRS-1, and phospho-JNK were similar in both groups. CONCLUSION(S): Skeletal muscle in patients with PCOS demonstrates changes associated with decreased glucose metabolism and a relative hyperinsulinemia. Our findings support a PCOS phenotype with a decreased oxidative capacity secondary to changes in fiber type, along with alterations at numerous points in insulin signaling pathways that affect the ability of skeletal muscle to increase uptake of glucose.
