4075. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72226717
T1  - Pregnancy following letrozole treatment in infertile women with PCOS or unexplained infertility has low risk of congenital anomalies and serious adverse events
T3  - 63rd Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2016. Montreal, QC Canada.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Eisenberg E.
A1  - Diamond M.P.
A1  - Legro R.S.
A1  - Huang H.
A1  - Zhang H. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Prospectively collected data on pregnancy outcomes and risk of congenital anomalies in conceptions following exposure to medications for ovarian stimulation is sparce. Patients and clinicians need reliable information to aid in selecting appropriate treatment. Letrozole is approved for the adjuvant treatment of breast cancer and is used off label to stimulate ovulation in infertile women. Key issues for the use of letrozole are pregnancy outcomes and risk of teratogenicity. METHOD(S): We sought to identify adverse effects of ovarian stimulation with letrozole compared to clomiphene citrate (CC) or gonadotropins (Gn) on pregnancy outcomes in an observational cohort of infertile women who conceived in the PPCOSII and AMIGOS clinical trials conducted by the Reproductive Medicine Network. Data on pregnancy loss, pregnancy related complications and congenital anomalies were collected prospectively. Statistical analysis was with chi-square or Fisher's exact test for categorical data; for continuous data, Wilcoxon rank-sum test was used to test differences between two groups and Kruksal-Wallis test to test differences among groups of three or more. RESULT(S): A total of 572 pregnancies were conceived with medical treatment: 232 with letrozole, 201 with CC, 139 with Gn, and 18 were conceived spontaneously. Baseline characteristics were comparable in all treatment groups. Outcomes of pregnancy loss, serious adverse events, antenatal and post-partum complication and congenital anomaly rates were comparable among the groups, though hyperemesis and mixed pregnancy (loss+live birth) were significantly increased in the Gn group, and gestational diabetes was significantly increased in pregnancies conceived with letrozole and CC. Congenital anomalies occurred in 3% of all deliveries with no difference among treatment groups. CONCLUSION(S): Ovarian stimulation with letrozole is associated with comparable pregnancy outcomes as CC and similar low risk of congenital anomalies as other medications used for ovarian stimulation.
