4078. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72226125
T1  - Regulation of mitogenic insulin receptor a in human endometrial epithelium is estrogen independent
T3  - 63rd Annual Scientific Meeting of the Society for Gynecologic Investigation, SGI 2016. Montreal, QC Canada.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Flannery C.A.
A1  - Saleh F.I.
A1  - Choe G.H.
A1  - Kodaman P.H.
A1  - Wood T.L.
A1  - Taylor H.S. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - INTRODUCTION: Women with obesity, PCOS, or type 2 diabetes are at higher risk endometrial cancer, even after menopause, suggesting that hyperinsulinemia may contribute to pathogenesis. We previously demonstrated that the metabolic insulin receptor isoform B (IR-B) is highest during the secretory phase when glands synthesize glycogen. However, mitogenic isoform IR-A increases dramatically during the early proliferative phase. We initially hypothesized IR-A and IR-B are regulated by estradiol or progesterone, respectively. METHOD(S): To determine cell specific receptor distribution and regulation, epithelial and stromal cells were isolated from the endometrium of normal cycling women (n=26). IR expression levels were analyzed in cell lysates. Cells were also cultured and treated for 6 hours with estradiol (E2) 10nM, progesterone (P4)1muM, combined E2 and P4, or 0.1% ethanol (vehicle). IR-A and IR-B mRNA were quantified by qRT-PCR. RESULT(S): Each receptor was expressed in both cell types in all phases of the menstrual cycle. A dramatic increase in IR-A during the proliferative phase occurred predominantly in the epithelial cells (p=0.03, vs. stromal). In contrast, IR-B was higher in epithelial cells during the secretory phase than proliferative phase (p=0.05). In stromal cells, IR-A and IR-B was relatively stable throughout the cycle. IR-A and IR-B were unchanged in epithelial cells treated with E2, P4, or combined, relative to vehicle (p=NS). In stromal cells IR-A was modestly increased 1.4-fold after estradiol treatment (p<=0.01) while IR-B levels were not significantly altered by either estradiol or progesterone (p=NS). CONCLUSION(S): The dramatic rise of IR-A in epithelial cells during the proliferative phase indicates IR-A is the predominant isomer responsible for glandular proliferation in normal endometrial physiology. The lack of direct regulation of IR-A by E2 in epithelial cells aligns with IR-A's rapid increase in epithelial cells in the early proliferative phase when E2 levels are low. IR-A modulates early growth of normal endometrial epithelium prior to a rise in estrogens. Similarly, estrogen independent IR-A regulation of endometrial mitogenic activity is a likely mechanism for endometrial hyperplasia and cancer in post-menopausal diabetic women.
