4081. 
TY  - JOUR
DB  - Embase
AN  - 72164865
T1  - Prenatal care in a specialized diabetes in pregnancy program improves compliance with postpartum testing
T3  - 36th Annual Meeting of the Society for Maternal-Fetal Medicine: The Pregnancy Meeting. Atlanta, GA United States.
T3  - (var.pagings).
A1  - Durnwald C.P.
A1  - Huynh T.
A1  - Ghaffari N.
A1  - Bastek J. 
Y1  - 2016//
N2  - OBJECTIVE: Adherence to postpartum (PP) testing in women with gestational diabetes (GDM) is poor. The influence of a specialized disease-focused prenatal care clinic to improve compliance for follow up is not well studied. We sought to evaluate whether prenatal care in a specialized, multidisciplinary Diabetes in pregnancy program (DMC) improves compliance with completion of the 2 hour 75 gram oral glucose tolerance test (2HrOGTT) in women with GDM. STUDY DESIGN: A retrospective cohort study of GDM women delivering in a university health system between Jan 2011-March 2014 was performed. Women were divided into 2 groups: those in routine prenatal clinics over an 18 month period prior to establishment of a specialized DMC (pre-DMC) and those in prenatal care in the specialized DMC staffed by Maternal Fetal Medicine(post-DMC). There was a 6 month washout period. GDM was diagnosed by: 1 hour 50g GCT of >= 200 or 3 hour 100g OGTT meeting Carpenter/ Coustan criteria. The primary outcome was completion of the 2HrOGTT in the PP period. Clinical characteristics associated with completion of the 2HrOGTT were evaluated. Chi square, t-test and Mann Whitney U were used where appropriate. Time trend analysis was used to evaluate month to month variation in 2HrOGTT compliance to evaluate for secular trends. RESULT(S): A total of 292 women were analyzed, 118 pre-DMC and 147 post-DMC. The 2HrOGTT was ordered more frequently in the post-DMC period compared to pre-DMC (90.0 vs 53.0%, p<0.0001). Rates of completion of the 2HrOGTT was 25.0% pre- DMC and 49.2% post-DMC, p=0.007. Clinical characteristics associated with 2HrOGTT completion are listed in Table 1. After adjusting for history of PCOS and BMI at last visit, women who received prenatal care post- DMC were 2.98 times more likely to complete the 2HrOGTT in the PP period compared to those receiving care pre-DMC (OR 2.98 [1.34, 6.62], p=0.007). CONCLUSION(S): GDM women who receive prenatal care in a specialized diabetes in pregnancy program are more likely to complete the 2HrOGTT in the postpartum period. Increasing adherence to postpartum testing in these women at risk for Type 2 diabetes could improve long term maternal health. (Table Presented).
